In total, 106 patients completed this study. Most patients were married, and the majority of the participants were male. The average age of the study population was 62.07 ± 9.08 (32–81). By localization, the age distribution was: oral (58.22 ± 12.27 (32–77)), larynx (62.97 ± 7.97 (42-61.78)), and pharynx (61.78 ± 10.11 (50–80)). The majority presented with stage II and III HNC, while only 2.8% presented with stage IV. The most common tumor site was the larynx. Planocellular carcinoma was confirmed in the majority of participants. A tracheostomy was performed in nearly half of the participants (Table 
1
).

The confirmatory factor analysis model specified five factors (subscales), validating the factor structure of a FACT-HN questionnaire (Fig. 
1
).

The convergent validity was adequate when compared with the EORTC-QLQ30 questionnaire, for all components, with a range of 0.555–0.754, but low for the SWB component (0.288). The total FACT-HN score was highly correlated to the EORTC-QLQ30 (Table 
2
). With regard to the other questionnaires, GAD-7 and CES-D, had a high correlation to the subscales regarding mental health (EWB and FWB).

Correlation between the EORTCHN43 was highly correlated to the HNCS subscale of the FACT-HN. The highest correlations with the HNCS subscale were observed in dimensions assessing pain in the mouth, swallowing, problems with teeth, dry mouth and sticky saliva, speech, body image, social eating, sexuality, and social contact (Table 
3
).

The questionnaire evaluated five constructs: PWB, SWB, EWB, FWB, and HNCS. The Cronbach’s α values for all constructs were positive, demonstrating the questionnaire’s validity and the consistency of responses. Among the constructs, FWB exhibited the highest internal consistency, with a range of 0.821 to 0.871 (Table 
4
). The removal of items in the examined subscales did not significantly improve reliability (increase Cronbach’s α coefficients).
